<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-244-372  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 244 372.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  March 15 1990 n1385* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Comten offers IBM 3745 users Open Systems simplification. (NCRCorp.'s NCR Comten)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   NCR Comten Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Comten Open Systems Interconnection/Communications Processor(Communications software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionCommunications SoftwareConnectivityOSI StandardTransmission Control Protocol-Internet Protocol (Computer NetworkProtocol)SNA.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>COMTEN OFFERS IBM 3745 USERS OPEN SYSTEMS SIMPLIFICATIONandM;NCR Corp's NCR Comten in St Paul, Minnesota continues to outdo IBM in thecommunications processor field, and its latest offering on its 56X5 series ofalternatives to IBM's 3745 front-end is a new package designed to integrateOpen Systems Interconnection applications with TCP/IP and SNA over a singlenetwork backbone.andP;  The company says that the Comten Open SystemsInterconnection/Communications Processor software makes it possible for opensystems applications like file transfer and electronic mail to operate overwide area networks independent of mainframes on the network, saving usersline costs, increasing the the efficiency of network routing and freeing themainframe for applications processing.andP;  Without the software, Comten says,users need separate lines for their open systems and TCP/IP traffic and forSNA.andP;  It also reduces the need for single-purpose bridges, routers andancillary processors - such as IBM's 8232 LAN Channel Station and 3172Interconnect Controller when alien open systems need to access IBM opensystems or SNA applications.andP;  It enables Ethernetworks to be integrated intothe network without the need for bridges and gateways, and provides access toIBM's OSI/File Services, OSI/X400, Open Systems Message Exchnage, SNA/X400Profs and SNA/DisOSS, Comten says.andP;  The software implements layers one tofour of the seven layer open systems reference model, and will be availablein the fourth quarter of this year at $7,000 upfront, plus $200 a month.andO;</TEXT></DOC>